arts.ttl: Reading boss on Harborough Town FA Cup victory, squad rotation and Kanu red card
arts.sum: Reading boss Ruben Selles is using Sunday's 5-3 win over Harborough Town in the FA Cup as a useful 'learning' exercise for his young squad. The Royals battled hard and needed extra time to scrape past the seventh tier outfit but are in the hat for the third round draw on Monday. Charlie Savage, Adrian Akande and Chem Campbell's brace did the damage, while the Bees lead in the first half and equalised in the final 10 minutes of normal time to force an extra 30 minutes. Speaking after the victory, Selles said: "We know with these games in the FA Cup that it doesn’t matter who the opponent is- they presented a team that had a clear idea. We knew it and I think it is a part of our journey as a team, to get exposed to the massive pressure.

arts.ttl: 10-man Reading require extra time to squeeze past non-league side in FA Cup classic
arts.sum: Reading narrowly avoided an FA Cup upset by beating seventh tier outfit Harborough Town 5-3 but needed extra time and played more than three-quarters-of-an-hour with 10 men. Freddie Robinson and Riley O’Sullivan netted either side of Mamadi Camara’s goal to lead at half-time, but goals from Charlie Savage and Adrian Akande had Ruben Selles’ side progressing into round three by the 75th minute. A red card for Abraham Kanu gave the Bees plenty of encouragement and Kai Tonge took the game into extra time with an equaliser in the final five minutes. Ultimately, two goals in two minutes from Chem Campbell took the tie away from the Bees of Leicestershire, who were backed by over 2,800 supporters in full voice. In what was essentially began as one long match of ‘Attack versus Defence’, the visitors set out their stall from the start and were content with defending deep, clearing their lines and playing for set pieces.
